[~] 2.  DEPENDENCIES (enumerate now; install via uv)
    [x] 2.1.  Runtime (required):
        [x] 2.1.1.  mcp — the official MCP Python SDK; bundles FastMCP.
                    Import: `from mcp.server.fastmcp import FastMCP`.
                    Pinned `mcp>=1.2` (resolved 1.28.0).
        [x] 2.1.2.  Python >= 3.10 (FastMCP requirement) — requires-python set.
        [x] 2.1.3.  Version read at runtime from package metadata via
                    importlib.metadata (stdlib) — NO extra dep. Wired in §4.3.
        [x] 2.1.4.  The skeleton's one tool (info) needs NOTHING beyond the
                    above. The GNU units ENGINE is a FUTURE dependency, not the
                    skeleton's — decide it in 2.4, wire it after section 9.
        [x] 2.1.5.  json-repair — pure-Python, zero-dep; the one extra runtime
                    dep, for the LLM-mangled-JSON tolerance wiring (§4.6).
                    Pinned `json-repair>=0.30` (resolved via lock).
    [x] 2.1.6.  FIXED-POINT NUMERIC CORE — ✅ DECIDED (2026-06-19): NO new dep.
                    The engine (§2.4 / FUTURE) needs fixed-point arithmetic that
                    also computes the number of decimals actually required and
                    labels each result exact vs inexact — the same numeric model
                    mcp-abacus exposes. Abacus does this with the Python STDLIB
                    ONLY: `decimal.Decimal` + `decimal.localcontext` (fixed-point
                    / exact-scaled-integer + per-op precision / rounding readout),
                    `fractions.Fraction` (exact rational), and `math` for floats.
                    Its sole external deps are `mcp` + `json-repair` — BOTH already
                    in our plan (§2.1.1, §2.1.5) — so the fixed-point math adds
                    NOTHING to dependencies.
                    POLICY: align with mcp-abacus's DEPENDENCY CHOICES where
                    feasible (stay on stdlib decimal/fractions; same mcp +
                    json-repair floors), but DO NOT share or copy mcp-abacus CODE
                    — we re-implement our own numeric core for the units engine.
                    Treat ../mcp-abacus as a READ-ONLY reference for the approach
                    (see its src/mcp_abacus/expr/value.py for the exact/inexact +
                    rounded-to-N-decimals verdict pattern), not a code source.
    [x] 2.2.  Dev / tooling:
        [x] 2.2.1.  uv — env, dependency resolution, lockfile (uv.lock generated
                    via `uv sync --extra dev`).
        [x] 2.2.2.  pytest — test runner (dev extra: pytest>=8.0).
        [ ] 2.2.3.  pytest-asyncio — NOT added (info() is sync; add lazily only
                    if a future tool is async).
        [x] 2.2.4.  ruff — lint + format (dev extra: ruff>=0.6; `ruff check` green).
        [x] 2.2.5.  mypy — optional static typing (dev extra: mypy>=1.11; configured).
    [x] 2.3.  Build backend: hatchling.
    [x] 2.4.  ENGINE — ✅ DECIDED (2026-06-19): SHIP A COPY of the GNU units
              database and parse it with OUR OWN pure-Python parser. NO reliance
              on a system `units(1)` binary.
              WHY (chosen over the subprocess approach): works cross-platform
              (Windows / macOS / Linux — no PATH or install dependency), faster
              (no process spawn per call), fully offline + genuinely deterministic
              (we PIN the DB version, so the frozen description's "deterministic"
              claim is now unconditionally true), and we own the engine. Bonus:
              no subprocess ⇒ no shell-injection / file-include / `!`-define
              attack surface to defend.
              OBLIGATIONS (checkable — flow from this decision):
        [x] 2.4.1.  Ship the DB VERBATIM (copyright header intact) at
                    src/mcp_gnu_units/data/definitions.units and force-include it
                    in BOTH wheel + sdist (§3.5) — it is PACKAGE DATA, not
                    importable code. DONE 2026-06-19 (commit 4f17938; verified in
                    both artifacts, sha256 matches source).
        [x] 2.4.2.  PIN + record the exact upstream version shipped — program +
                    data version, date, and checksums — so "deterministic" is
                    unconditionally true. DONE: GNU units 2.27, definitions.units
                    data v3.26 (2026-02-25); pins + SHA-256s + GPG verdict live
                    in NOTICE.
        [x] 2.4.3.  Add a NOTICE file crediting GNU units / the FSF
                    (GPL-3.0-or-later; our code is GPLv3 ⇒ wholly compatible),
                    and ship it in wheel + sdist. DONE 2026-06-19 (commit
                    c4126ed; ships via license-files + sdist include).
        [x] 2.4.4.  Document the bundled-data provenance in README. DONE —
                    "Bundled data & provenance" section, references NOTICE.
        [ ] 2.4.5.  Reference the bundled DB from the README HOMAGE section too
                    (the publish-time first-section homage to GNU units) —
                    tracked with §10.5.2. The provenance section (2.4.4) exists
                    now; the homage is still TODO.
        [ ] 2.4.6.  Surface the bundled DB version from info() (§5.4): extend
                    info() to report engine/database version. DEFERRED to engine
                    work (no engine yet).
        [x] 2.4.7.  Write the grammar/format spec for the DB language as the
                    parser's contract. DONE 2026-06-19 — docs/definitions-format.md
                    (EBNF + operator precedence incl. the juxtaposition-vs-`/`
                    footgun + directive reference, pinned to data v3.26, grounded
                    in the bundled file).
        [x] 2.4.8.  Build the pure-Python PARSER + evaluator per
                    docs/definitions-format.md, validated against the units(1)
                    binary as a test oracle. The units grammar has base + derived
                    units, SI/binary prefixes, nonlinear units (tempC/tempF, dB)
                    via functions, piecewise tables, and `!`/`!include`
                    directives. The big FUTURE ENGINE work — see §13. Also load
                    the DB at runtime via importlib.resources, NOT a relative
                    path (§3.5).
                    DONE 2026-06-19 — src/mcp_gnu_units/engine/ (15 modules):
                    number/dimension/quantity (exact Fraction-first numerics +
                    dimension algebra), lexer/ast/parser (recursive-descent
                    precedence ladder that encodes the juxtaposition-vs-`/`
                    footgun), symbols/directives/loader (one forward pass via
                    importlib.resources; conditional-block gating; logical-line
                    assembly), evaluator (name + longest-single-prefix + plural
                    resolution; nonlinear forward/inverse + `~`; table interp),
                    builtins (sqrt/cuberoot/log/trig), functions/tables, convert
                    (Database: convert/convert_to_si/reduce/find_units/
                    list_prefixes/describe + get_database singleton). Bare prefix
                    names resolve to their multiplier (`kilo`==1000); missing
                    `!include` targets (currency/crypto/elements) are skipped just
                    as the binary does. Tests: tests/engine/ (91 total) — golden
                    pins (1 mi→1.609344 km, 0 tempC→32 tempF, 1 kW·hour→3.6e6 J,
                    inconvertible errors cleanly) + a units(1) differential oracle
                    (`units -f` bundled DB, @skipif when absent). Differential
                    sweep over all 2938 SI-reducible derived units: 0 mismatches.
                    FOLLOW-ONS NOW UNBLOCKED: §2.4.6 (info DB version) and §13
                    (the 5 MCP tools) can call engine.get_database().
        [x] 2.4.9.  INVARIANT to uphold during engine work: pure-Python ⇒ NO new
                    runtime dependency (json-repair from §2.1.5 stays the only
                    extra). Verify at engine-merge time. VERIFIED 2026-06-19 —
                    engine uses only stdlib (decimal, fractions, importlib.
                    resources, re, math); dependencies still [mcp, json-repair].
                    The units(1) binary is a DEV/TEST oracle only (apt install
                    units), never shipped or called at runtime.


