[x] 4.  ARCHITECTURE / WIRING
    [x] 4.1.  server.py: singleton app built as `mcp = _GnuUnitsFastMCP(...)`
              (the FIX-B subclass, §4.6.3) with the §4.1 instructions string.
    [x] 4.2.  __main__.py: `main()` runs the stdio interposer (anyio runner, not
              bare mcp.run(), per §4.6.2) + `if __name__ == "__main__"` guard;
              imports the app from server.py so tools register on import.
              Runtime smoke: initialize handshake passes through the interposer.
    [x] 4.3.  __init__.py: expose `__version__` via
              importlib.metadata.version("mcp-gnu-units"), with a fallback for the
              editable/unbuilt case. (Done during §1 scaffolding; verified
              resolving to 0.0.1.)
    [x] 4.4.  Transport = stdio (FastMCP default via stdio_server). No HTTP/SSE.
    [x] 4.5.  Marked spots in server.py: §5 (info tool) + §4.5/FUTURE domain
              tools (convert/convert_to_si/find_units/define_unit/list_prefixes)
              — comments only, nothing built.
    [x] 4.6.  LLM-MANGLED-JSON TOLERANCE — make tool calls survive the broken
              JSON LLMs sometimes emit (stringified/double-encoded args, single
              quotes, trailing commas, barewords). Two failure layers → two
              fixes. SHORT step-by-step below; the FULL rationale + code is in the
              howto — FOLLOW it, do NOT copy verbatim:
                REF (why/how)    : ~/projects/mcp-abacus/llm-json-errors-howto.text
                REF IMPL (copy)  : ../mcp-bytesmith/src/mcp_bytesmith/ —
                                   jsonfix.py + errors.py, the _BytesmithFastMCP
                                   subclass in server.py, the stdio interposer in
                                   __main__.py. (READ-ONLY sibling; don't edit.)
        [x] 4.6.1.  Add the `json-repair` runtime dep (§2.1.5 / §3.2).
        [x] 4.6.2.  FIX A — stringified args (the #1 offender) die at the
                    session's STRICT validation BEFORE any tool hook, so they
                    can't be caught in a tool. Repair them in a STDIO STREAM
                    INTERPOSER: replace mcp.run() (§4.2) with an anyio runner that
                    repairs `arguments` while it is still loosely-typed
                    JSONRPCRequest.params. Put the repair fn in a new jsonfix.py;
                    GUARD isinstance(parsed, dict) and hand the ORIGINAL back on
                    failure (json-repair never raises — it coerces junk to ""/{} ).
                    Implemented in jsonfix.py (repair_arguments + process_incoming);
                    interposer wired in __main__.py.
        [x] 4.6.3.  FIX B — well-formed-but-wrong-shape args die later in
                    FastMCP's per-tool pydantic validation. Subclass FastMCP and
                    override call_tool to reshape the ValidationError (its
                    __cause__) into a one-line, field-naming, expected-vs-received
                    message in a new errors.py; leave tool-body errors untouched.
                    The subclass INSTANCE is the app (mcp = _GnuUnitsFastMCP(...),
                    §4.1). Implemented in errors.py (format_validation_error) +
                    the _GnuUnitsFastMCP.call_tool override in server.py.
        [x] 4.6.4.  When repair still can't produce an object, the interposer
                    answers FROM itself with an actionable -32700 parse error
                    (jsonfix._parse_error_reply). Runtime-verified over stdio.
        [x] 4.6.5.  TESTS — pure-fn tests (tests/test_jsonfix.py: each offender +
                    garbage-guard + router; tests/test_errors.py: expected-vs-
                    received + no pydantic URL) AND the raw-stdio END-TO-END test
                    (done in §7 once `info` existed: stringified args repaired &
                    run; unparseable -> actionable -32700). All green.
              SCOPE: behaviourless for well-formed input, so wire it WITH the
              skeleton; its payoff shows once the FUTURE domain tools take real
              arguments. Non-stdio transports (none in the skeleton) would need
              the interposer applied there too.


