    --------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Register the first of the five FUTURE domain tools (§13) as an actual MCP
    tool, on top of the engine's already-built Database.find_units()
    (src/mcp_gnu_units/engine/convert.py:113, reached via
    engine.get_database()). Wire it into server.py beside info() (§4.5/§5) on
    the same FastMCP app. Per-tool + per-parameter descriptions must be rich —
    they feed Glama's Tool-Definition-Quality grade (§13).
    [x] 14.1.  Basic SUB-STRING finding mode. DONE 2026-06-20. find_units(query,
               limit=50) registered in server.py (Annotated/pydantic Field params:
               `query` required min_length=1, `limit` bounded 1..500). Wraps
               engine.get_database().find_units() — case-insensitive substring
               over NAME or DEFINITION, prefixes excluded, results in DB-native
               order (ranking deferred to a later sub-item). Returns
               {query, count, results:[{name, definition}]}. Tests: tests/
               test_server.py (end-to-end via mcp.call_tool — meter hit, limit
               honoured, no-match empty; one-tool §7.3.1 assertion relaxed to
               "info + find_units registered") + tests/engine/test_convert.py
               (5 engine golden tests: name+definition match, case-insensitive,
               prefixes excluded, limit, no-match). 99 tests pass; ruff + mypy
               clean.
               (Later modes — fuzzy / dimension-conformable search — are separate
               sub-items, not part of 14.1.)
    [x] 14.2.  ENRICH each hit with kind + base reduction, so the AI can search
               AND triage in ONE call instead of following up with a describe
               per unit. DONE 2026-06-20. For every result add three fields, sourced
               from the engine's already-built Database.describe() (convert.py:135):
                 - `kind`       : "unit" | "primitive" | "function" | "table"
                                  (prefixes are still excluded from results).
                 - `dimension`  : base-unit signature, e.g. "kg m^2 / s^3" for
                                  power — lets the caller check conformability
                                  without a second call.
                 - `base_value` : the unit reduced to base/primitive units with
                                  its coefficient, e.g. horsepower -> "745.7 kg
                                  m^2 / s^3".
               base_value/dimension are best-effort: omitted for hits that do
               not reduce (functions, tables). Wire in server.py by mapping each
               (name, definition) hit through get_database().describe(name);
               engine.find_units() stays the pure matcher (returns tuples), so
               its golden tests are unchanged. Update the find_units docstring
               Returns/Example. Tests: extend tests/test_server.py (assert the
               three new keys appear and reduce correctly for a known unit).
               Implemented: server.find_units maps each hit through
               get_database().describe(name); describe() now renders `dimension`
               via _format_dimension (the "/"-separated form, matching
               base_value) instead of str(Dimension). Also landed alongside:
               find_units/describe `definition` no longer repeats the leading
               name token (loader stores the parsed `rest` in symbols.sources,
               not the raw line). Verified live through the MCP tool (horsepower
               variants distinguished by base_value in one call; tempF/wiregauge
               exercise the function + table best-effort branch). Tests: tests/
               test_server.py::test_find_units_enriches_hits_with_kind_and_reduction
               + tests/engine/test_convert.py::test_find_units_definition_omits_
               leading_name. 101 tests pass; ruff + mypy clean.
